faqSchema:
  - question: "When is the best time to do a Roth conversion?"
    answer: "The ideal time is during low-income years — between retirement and Social Security or RMDs. This lets you fill lower tax brackets with conversions before being pushed into higher brackets by required distributions."
  - question: "How much should I convert each year?"
    answer: "The optimal amount depends on your current tax bracket, future RMDs, IRMAA thresholds, and state taxes. We model multi-year scenarios to find the sweet spot — typically converting enough to fill your current bracket without triggering the next one."
  - question: "Will a Roth conversion affect my Medicare premiums?"
    answer: "Yes — conversion income counts toward IRMAA thresholds with a 2-year lookback. We plan conversions to stay below the $206,000 (married) threshold, or time larger conversions when the IRMAA impact is worth the long-term tax savings."
  - question: "What is the Roth 5-year rule?"
    answer: "Converted funds must stay in the Roth for 5 years to avoid a 10% penalty on withdrawals (if under 59½). Each conversion starts its own 5-year clock. After 59½, this rule doesn't apply."
  - question: "Should I convert my entire IRA to Roth at once?"
    answer: "Almost never. A single large conversion pushes you into the highest tax brackets and triggers massive IRMAA surcharges. Strategic multi-year conversions spread across lower brackets save significantly more in lifetime taxes."
